Recommendations:
We recommended and Management concurred to the following:
Issue a memorandum for all collectors/AOs to enforce daily/prompt and intact remittance of all collections, and to impose sanctions against erring collectors/AOs pursuant to pertinent laws, rules and regulations;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to closely and regularly monitor the remittances by collectors/tellers;
Review its internal control processes on the manner of collections and remittance and institute measures to curtail the delay in the deposits of these collections;
Assess the delegation of duties/tasks to collectors/AOs and consider any adjustments or reinforcements thereto, if necessary; and
Ensure provision of a more stable internet connection in concerned offices, and in instances of poor internet connection, instruct preparation of manual or alternative means of reporting collections and remittances within the prescribed period.

Recommendations:
We recommended and it was agreed that Management:
6.11.1 Review and consider providing additional manpower to the GSO, in coordination with the Human Resource Management Office, who will specifically take charge in handling the PPE accounts including the preparation and monitoring of the required Property Cards and reconciliation thereof with accounting records and other reports;
Require the Municipal Accounting Office to fast track the review, tracing, and reconciliation of the unaccounted PPE accounts and ensure preparation and updating of property ledger cards and PPE schedules for reconciliation with the GSO records;
Create and instruct the Inventory Committee to prioritize undertaking the procedures indicated in COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account. Considering the bulk of its PPE accounts, the management may consider conduct of one-time cleansing per account basis, specifically, but not limited to the unaccounted PPE accounts totaling ₱166.602 million; and
Ensure that physical count of PPE be conducted regularly and the corresponding RPCPPE be prepared and submitted accordingly.

Recommendations:
We recommended and Management is amenable to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare and fast track the reconciliation of the unadjusted / unidentified Due to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth account balances to identify under/over remittances, and take appropriate actions to ensure full remittance thereof within the prescribed period and/or make refunds to concerned employees, if warranted;
Ensure thereafter that all applicable contributions and loan payments are remitted timely to avoid late payment charges, interests and penalties.  Also, make sure that such remittances / payments are accurately reflected in the bank without reversals;
Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for the Due to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth accounts, and closely monitor the contributions withheld and loan repayments and remittances thereof;
Effect the proposed correcting entry for the Intra-Bank Fund Transfers related to online payments of inter-agency payables as shown in Annex P;
Institute measures to recover the penalty and interest incurred for the June 2024 PhilHealth remittances from the responsible employees; and
Review / assess the roles of personnel assigned in the reconciliation of the discrepancies, and consider assigning additional staff to expedite the process.

Recommendations:
8.12 We recommended and Management concurred to require the Municipal Accounting Office to:
Fast track and prioritize the reconciliation of the remittance and billing files to resolve outstanding discrepancies totaling ₱0.601 million;
Identify and resolve the discrepancy of ₱1.125 million between the balance of under- or over-remittance recorded per books under the 'Due to GSIS' account and per UPR;
Coordinate with the HRMO in updating the service records and maintaining close coordination with the GSIS by promptly submitting the required documents; and
Review / assess the roles of personnel assigned in the retrieval of documents and reconciliation thereof, and consider assigning additional staff to expedite the process.

Recommendations:
We recommended and it was agreed that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to fast-track and exert effort in retrieving previous accounting records to properly establish the details of the beginning account balances of the Inventories, and thereafter coordinate with the GSO to validate the existence of these Inventories;
Require the GSO to regularly and fully conduct semestral physical count of inventories and prepare/submit the corresponding inventory reports using the prescribed RCPI form, furnishing the Auditor a copy thereof;
Instruct the GSO and the Municipal Accountant to prepare/maintain stock cards and Supplies Ledger Cards, both per stock number, respectively, and conduct regular reconciliation of their respective records / reports on Inventories; and
Assess and consider providing additional manpower, in coordination with the Human Resource Management Office, to the GSO to cope up with the voluminous and various tasks assigned to that office.

Recommendations:
We recommended and Management concurred to the following:
Require the GSO, in coordination with concerned releasing offices/units such as the RHU and MAO, to ensure proper preparation of the SSMIs, that only inventories which are already released to the ultimate end users shall be issued with the RISs and reported in the SMI;
Instruct the concerned end-users such as the RHU and MAO to prepare their own supplies inventory records and keep track of the issuances / releases to ultimate end-users, and furnish the GSO a report thereon as basis in the preparation of the SSMI;
Direct the Accounting Office to timely recognize expenses out of the issuances of Inventories based on the SSMI received from the GSO, and refrain from requiring RSMIs in the payment of purchases to avoid premature recognition of expenses out of unissued inventory supplies; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to investigate the discrepancy of P24M and consequently record the necessary adjustments on the noted misstatement.

Recommendation:
We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare and fast track the reconciliation of the unadjusted Due to BIR account balance, and take appropriate actions to ensure full remittance thereof within the prescribed period and take up necessary adjustments in the books and related records / BIR forms;
18.17.2 Ensure correct and prompt remittance of taxes withheld to avoid unnecessary penalties;
Institute measures to improve the withholding and remittance of taxes to ensure that the unremitted taxes at year-end only include those withheld during the last month of the year;
18.17.4 Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledger for the Due to BIR account, and closely monitor the taxes withheld and remittances thereof; and
Review / assess the roles of personnel assigned in the reconciliation of the discrepancies, and consider assigning additional staff to expedite the process.

We have recommended that the Management undertake the following:

A.	Create an Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of all PPEs of the Municipality, whether acquired through purchase or donation, including those constructed by administration and found at station;

B.	Thru the Inventory Committee created, update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile with accounting records;

C.	Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and 

D.	After the inventory taking, direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the updated ledger cards for each item of the PPE.

We have recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

A.	Coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer to confirm the status of the checks reported as outstanding to determine whether these were issued to the payees or cancelled checks; 

B.	Exert effort to review the long outstanding/stale checks and require the Municipal Treasurer to cancel the unclaimed stale checks and to furnish the Accounting Office with the original Disbursement Vouchers and its supporting documents, for the preparation of the Journal Entry Voucher, following the procedures prescribed to ensure recording of such cancellation;

C.	Secure Monthly Bank Statements to prepare the Bank Reconciliation Statements to determine whether checks claimed by the payees were presented for payment, and secure the addresses of the payees for notification of the return of stale checks in their possession for replacement; and

D.	Draw the JEV to restore the cash and liabilities pertaining to the stale checks to present fairly the recorded Cash in Bank and accounts payable accounts.

We have recommended the following to the Management:

A.	Submit justification on why the payments were approved despite the absence of an appropriation;

B.	Ensure that overtime services are provided with an appropriation under the Personal Services budget of the Municipality; 

C.	Require the Municipal Budget Officer to stop the practice of charging expenditures against appropriations that are intended for other purpose or specific purpose;

D.	Require the Municipal Accountant to appropriately record the payment of overtime services; 

E.	Submit justification on why the Department Heads were allowed to render overtime work with pay;

F.	Require the Department Heads to judiciously plan their tasks/activities to avoid requesting for overtime services; and

G.	Require the Municipal Accountant ensure that payments for overtime services are supported with complete documentation.

