We recommended that Management:
Exhaust all possible means to require the concerned officers and employees to liquidate/settle immediately their outstanding cash advances by demanding the immediate submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports or to refund the cash still in their possession;
Avoid granting subsequent cash advances to AOs with outstanding cash advances and withhold the salaries and/or any amount due those AOs who were unable to comply with the pertinent rules and regulations on cash advances in accordance with the afore-cited law and regulations;
Strictly comply with the requirements of Section 89 of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 97-002, COA Circular No. 2012-001, and all related rules and regulations pertaining to cash advances; and
Follow-up with the COA-ICFAU on the issuance of credit advice pertaining to submitted liquidation reports on cash advances for intelligence expenses in the amount of ₱2,483,500.00.

We reiterated our audit recommendations that Management:
Direct the Local DRRM Officer-Designate to prepare the annual LDRRMFIP detailing all the PPAs to be funded in accordance with COA Circular 2012-002 to ensure proper evaluation of the same;
Enjoin the Local DRRM Officer-Designate to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities and to closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to revert back the unexpended balance of LDRRMF for CY 2018 amounting to ₱3,941,076.07 to the unappropriated surplus of the GF in which it had been available for five years in the Trust Fund and to record the Construction in Progress – MDRRMO Building in the General Fund books; and
Require the Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to transfer the unutilized balance of the LDRRMF from the General Fund to the Trust Fund under the account Trust Liability – DRRM. Ensure that the unexpended balance of QRF and LDRRF – MOOE for each year be timely transferred at year-end with the corresponding cash back up in order to reflect the correct balance of the cash and liability accounts in the FS.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to appropriate the 5 percent GAD Fund from the total annual budget in compliance with Item 4.1.C.1 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 to effectively promote the general welfare and provision of basic services and facilities for the Agency’s gender-responsiveness;
Reconstitute the composition of the GFPS ExeCom and TWG in accordance with Item 4.1.A of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 to further strengthen the GFPS and accelerate gender mainstreaming in the Municipality;
Prepare the GAD Agenda to align the PPAs to the administration’s plan with respect to the implementation of GAD mandates to ensure the promotion of gender equality and empowerment of involved parties;
Require the GFPS Chairperson to submit the GPB and GAD AR for CY 2023 and observe the required timelines in the submission of the GPB and GAD AR in accordance with the aforecited provisions of COA Circular 2014-001;
Comply with the provisions of Section 3 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01 by subjecting the GAD PPAs to the GAD/HGDG Checklist during the project identification and designing programs to determine whether the same fully address the gender issues and concerns of the locality; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain the corresponding SL for GAD-related accounts for an effective and efficient monitoring of GAD-related expenses and preparation of necessary reports.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accounting Office to:
Submit the BRS within the prescribed period and regularly adjust reconciling items;
Exert extra effort in tracing and adjusting the long outstanding unreconciled items, otherwise, initiate the request for write-off thereof in accordance with the provisions under COA Circular No. 97-001;
Refer to the Schedule of Unreleased Checks for the preparation of the adjusting entry to restore the value of the unreleased checks to the cash account balance and set-up the appropriate liability, and make an entry the following year to reverse such adjustments. Also, regular coordination with the Treasurer and vice versa relative to this matter and all other concerns of the agency involving the Accounting and Treasury Offices is highly encouraged; and
Conduct proper investigation on the long outstanding deposits in transit and recognize a receivable from the identified erring employee/officer, if any.
Direct the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to:
Send notices to the payees concerned on the existence of stale checks;
Ensure preparation of the Schedule of Unreleased Checks, a list of checks which are unreleased or undelivered at the end of the year, and submission thereof to the Municipal Accountant.
Evaluate the current manning composition of the Accounting Office and consider possible additions to the manpower including the personnel in charge of the preparation of BRS.

We recommended that Management require the following:
That any loss of accountable forms under the custody of the AO be immediately reported by the concerned AO to the Municipal Treasurer and/or the Municipal Mayor who, in turn, correspondingly issue the Notice of Loss and cause the publication / circularization thereof, if necessary, pursuant to the aforementioned provisions of COA Circular No. 84-233 and the LTOM, with the instruction that the Municipality be informed at once by the office / individual concerned if the said OR was issued in the latter’s favor;
That the AOs of the Municipality exercise due diligence in the custodianship of government funds, properties and accountable forms, and that in case of loss thereof, relief from accountability be requested following the requirements procedures and requirements set forth in COA Circular No. 92-386;
In the absence of request for relief from accountability for lost funds, properties or accountable forms, the loss shall be taken up as a receivable from the concerned AO; and
Ensure that all AOs, officers and employees concerned be duly oriented as to their duties and responsibilities pertaining to the handling / custody of funds, properties or accountable forms, and be supervised properly and accordingly, and that their respective accountabilities be monitored regularly as required in the above-mentioned provision of the NGAS Manual for LGUS.

We recommended that Management:
In coordination with the Human Resource/Personnel Unit, evaluate / assess the Accounting Office’s and GSO’s current manpower whether it is sufficient enough to cater / accommodate the demands of the office, and based on the results of the assessment, make and/or suggest necessary adjustments in the composition, number and qualification of personnel to address the concerns of the undermanned offices;
Instruct the Inventory Committee and GSO to complete the physical count of all PPEs and furnish complete reports using the prescribed format of the RPCPPE;
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to prepare / maintain the PPELCs and PCs, respectively, and thereafter ensure regular reconciliation thereof and other related records;
Require the Municipal Accountant to update the Subsidiary Ledgers for each class of PPE account to provide reliable details or breakdown of and to properly support the balances appearing in the General Ledger;
Direct the Inventory Committee, Property Custodian and the Municipal Accountant to conduct reconciliation of data in the RPCPPE with the accounting and property records; and
Consider conducting the one-time cleansing of PPE in which upon completion of the proper conduct of physical count:
Instruct the Supply Officer to determine the person/s accountable for any non-existing/missing PPEs based on the Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs), PCs and other available property records, and thereafter issue demand letters to produce the missing PPE; and
Direct the Inventory Team, the Supply Officer and the Municipal Accountant to refer to Sections 7 to 9 of the same COA circular for the procedures in the disposition and derecognition of any non-existing/missing PPEs.

