strictly require the weekly SSMI so as to support of the recording of issuances as expense pursuant to Section 121 of NGAS Manual Vol. 1; and

semestrally conduct of the physical count of inventory items by type and Submit the required Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RCPI) to the auditor.

We recommended that Management:

1.	Pursuant to COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, create an Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of all PPEs of the Municipality, whether acquired through purchase or donation, including those constructed by administration and found at station;

2. 	Thru the Inventory Committee created, update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs;

3. 	Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and 

4. 	After the inventory taking, direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the updated ledger cards for each item of the PPE pursuant to the Section 269 of the GAM for LGUs.

We recommended the management to:
a) 	Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct a physical count of Property, Plant and Equipment and require the submission of the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) giving priority to its Lands and, if possible, provide additional manpower to its inventory taking process in order to assure its completion and submission;
b) 	Direct the Municipal Accountant and Property Officer to establish its own Subsidiary Ledgers and corresponding Property Ledger Cards for each parcel of land and further reconcile the PPE balances once the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) is completed and submitted in compliance with Section 120 - Vol. 1 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs;
c) 	Direct the Municipal Assessor, Accountant and the GSO to constantly reconcile their records to reflect an accurate, reliable and correct balance of the Land in the financial statement; and

d)   Exhaust all possible means to document the legality of ownership over all parcel of lands through Transfer Certificate of Titles (TCT) in the name of the Municipality and to ensure that the LGU has legal rights over all recognized assets in its financial statements.

We recommended the management to:
a. 	Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects to the Municipal Accountant so that the latter may record them separately in the ledger cards of each Road Network;
b. 	Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the Registry of Public Infrastructure and establish separate subsidiary ledgers and Ledger Cards for each Local Road Network and its components (see Annex D of COA Circular 2015-008). These ledgers shall be kept in the accounting division and shall be maintained for each local road;
c. 	Require the General Services Office to prepare and maintain an Inventory of all Local Roads, Road Map and Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components (see Annex E of the said circular). Likewise, the preparation of Report of Local Road Network must be observed yearly by the GSO;
d. 	Create a sub-committee or group under the Municipal Inventory Committee that will primarily handle the inventory of local road network system; and
e. 	Require the Municipal Accountant to provide adjusting journal entries to recognize its local road networks in its books of accounts and disclose the road networks in the Notes to the Financial Statements. Further, depreciation shall be computed separately, supported with a lapsing schedule, for road components taking into consideration its useful life and initial cost.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accounting Office to prioritize the reconciliation process and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly;
Require the Municipal Accounting Office concerned personnel to maintain complete and updated PPELCs to support GL account balances and the Municipal Treasury Office concerned personnel to keep corresponding Property Cards for control purposes;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to continue tracing back prior years’ acquisitions of PPE to have a complete detail of the PPE accounts so that the corresponding depreciation could be computed, to present fairly the carrying value of the depreciable PPE; and
Continue exerting efforts in completing the physical count and in having a complete and accurate RPCPPE in relation to the deficiencies noted.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Reconcile thoroughly the balances per book and per bank to determine the valid reconciling items and prepare the necessary adjustments in the books for all the errors committed in the books and notify the bank immediately of any errors they may have been committed in order to arrive at a correct Cash in Bank account;
Ensure that all valid reconciling items to be recorded and adjusted in the books are properly supported with complete documents;
Maintain SLs for each Cash in Bank - LCCA under all funds in accordance with Section 10 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume II;
Prepare the BRS every month upon receipt of the bank statements and submit promptly to the Office of the Auditor for audit and verification, in accordance with COA Circular No. 96-011; and
Exercise due diligence and professional care in the conduct of reconciliation of records and in the performance of functions especially in the recording of journal entries and mathematical computation thereof.
We likewise recommended that the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer fully investigate the unreconciled balances of Cash in Bank - LCCA accounts for all funds and prepare the necessary adjustments to reconcile the accounting and the treasury records. Thereafter, a reconciliation of both records must be made on a monthly basis.

We recommended that Management:
Designate a Special Disbursing Officer to ensure the availability of cash for the immediate release of AICS;
Stop the practice of granting cash assistance to clients or person in the absence of documentary requirements. The submission of complete documentary requirements for each type of assistance are condition precedent to the payment; and
Prepare and issue a well-defined set of policies and guidelines governing the implementation of AICS program which must be aligned with the guidelines issued by the DSWD governing the grants of AICS. The policies and guidelines must contain the following:
Kind of financial assistance (burial, transportation, medical, educational, food, shelter and others);
Limitations on the amounts given per kind of financial assistance;
Criteria in granting the financial assistance and the documentary requirements for each particular case; and
Well defined roles and responsibilities of the officials processing requests.

We recommended that Management:
Enjoin the LDRRMO to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities;
Closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization;
Direct the Local DRRM Officer-Designate to prepare the annual LDRRMFIP detailing all the PPAs to be funded in accordance with COA Circular 2012-002 to ensure proper evaluation of the same;
Advise the Municipal Budget Officer see to it that all charges in the LDRRMF are related to four thematic areas of disaster risk reduction and management as prescribed in NDRRMC, DBM and DILG JMC 2013-1; and
Instruct the LDRRMC to prioritize the utilization of the unexpended balances of LDRRMF for CYs 2017 to 2020 to ensure that these funds are used for the intended purpose within the prescribed period.
We also recommended that the unexpended balance of LDRRMF for CY 2016 amounting to ₱2,925,434.15, which had been available for more than five years in the Trust Fund, be reverted back to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund.

We recommended that Management:
Expedite the completion/updating of the 10-year Municipal SWM Plan for approval by the NSWMC to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction;
Prioritize SWM programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation;
Provide the necessary training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized; and
Exert continuous effort in preserving and protecting the environment by implementing the environmental laws as mandated under RA No. 9003.

We recommend that management:

Strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular 2009-001 in the timeline to submit the perfected purchase orders/ contract within 5 calendar days;

b)Send invitation letter to the Office of the Auditor to conduct inspection of deliveries with sufficient lead time to plan and assigned personnel form this Office to observe the inspection;

c)Require a refund from the supplier commensurate to the deficiency/under delivery noted; and 

d)Require an explanation from the GSO and the Inspectorate team why an administrative case shall not be filed against them for accepting deliveries not specified in the PO.

We recommended that management:

Strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular 2004-006 in the use of Reimbursable Expense Receipt in order to be considered as an acceptable evidence of receipt of payment to ensure the completeness of the required supporting documents in the disbursement of government funds; 

require and demand each recipient Barangay the issuance of an Official Receipt of the funds received from the LGU; 

demand from the Punong Barangays the submission of the Liquidation Reports, Purchase Orders/Contracts and required supporting documents evidencing the disbursement of the funds related to the conduct of Araw ng Claveria activities to be submitted to the Municipal Accountant; and 

Reclassify the accounts that were expensed outright by debiting Due from LGUs to establish the receivables from Barangays pending their liquidation of the amounts received.

We recommended that management:

Should strictly adhere to the provisions of RA 7160 and DEPED-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1 series of 2017 in the proper use and utilization of the SEF to avoid subsequent Notice of Suspension or Disallowance;

Submit the liquidation reports and supporting documents, aside from the attached RER, evidencing the utilization of the Teacher’s Month subsidy;

Should require the payees of check number 3377503 dated September 27, 2019 to submit a duly approved Authority to Travel signed by the DepEd Regional Director;

Submit a justification why the four participants who were not members of the Municipal School Board but were allowed to join the said National Education Summit;

Require the four participants to submit a duly signed Memorandum/Letter/Order/Invitation to support their Authority to Travel.

We recommend that Management:

1.	require the proponents to submit the lacking supporting documents in order to prove the validity and propriety of the disbursements and to avoid suspensions and disallowances;

2.	should not grant subsequent educational researches without observing the guidelines set forth in the Department Order No. 16, s. 2017 dated March 20, 2017;

3.	should submit a justification/explanation on the inconsistencies of the signatures appearing in the payroll for CY 2018 and 2019; and

